                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName>
                                        <date>March 13, 1850</date>.</p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Rev. Mr. Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Your letter in reply to mine<lb/> was duly
                                        received, and I do feel ashamed to reply<lb/> at this late
                                        date. But charitably suspend your judg-<lb/>ment for a
                                        moment and let me give my various excuses.<lb/> In the first
                                        place I was unwell when I received your<lb/> letter, and by
                                        venturing out the next day I injured my-<lb/>self seriously.
                                        During part of <date>January</date>, the whole of the
                                        last<lb/> month, and up to this date I have been almost
                                        every day<lb/> confined to my room by a bronchial affection,
                                        and it was<lb/> unfortunate that I made an exception of two
                                        days, and ven-<lb/>tured to walk out. I have had to leave
                                                  <persName>Mr. Goldsmith's</persName>.<lb/> In
                                        these circumstances I have felt inclined to let every
                                        thing<lb/> else stand still, and attend to myself.</p>
                              <p>Not being fit to go out, I have tried to attend to<lb/> your matter
                                        by writing, and to <sic>fulfil</sic> my promise to use<lb/>
                                        my best efforts to secure the publication of anything that
                                        you<lb/> desire. I wrote immediately to <persName>I
                                                  Engles</persName> of your city, edi-<lb/>tor of
                                        the Presbyterian, giving strong reasons why I thought<lb/>
                                        he should publish your sermon. I requested him either<lb/>
                                        to write to me or to send in his consent to you, and
                                        gave<lb/> him your number. But ever since I have looked
                                        in</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>vain for your Sermon in the Presbyterian, and I have<lb/> received
                                        no private reply. It is notwithstanding due to the<lb/>
                                        liberality of this Editor to say that he immediately
                                        pub-<lb/>lished <persName>Dr. Schelsinger's</persName>
                                        Reply. I next wrote to the Editor<lb/> of the New York
                                        Observer, but I am sorry to say I never<lb/> received any
                                        reply. I have written to other editors whose<lb/>
                                        publications are read by all the members of the Synod,<lb/>
                                        and without yet promising unconditionally to publish
                                        your<lb/> Sermon, they raise questions about its length
                                        &amp;c. and say<lb/> they wish first to see it. So I hope I
                                        can accomplish<lb/> what you request, if you will send your
                                        Sermon to me<lb/>
                                        <placeName>122 Broome street</placeName>. Please have it
                                        carefully and plainly<lb/> written, and if it should be very
                                        long perhaps you would<lb/> not object to dividing it in the
                                        publication. For my<lb/> letters to the Editors I have urged
                                        as well as I could,<lb/> that we have read too much about
                                        the Jews from Christi-<lb/>ans and proselytes and that it is
                                        an act of justice<lb/> which we owe to them to let them
                                        explain themselves<lb/> in our hearing. So I will expect
                                        soon to re-<lb/>ceive your sermon.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I am very willing to write in the next volume<lb/>
                                        of the Occident as you propose, and to occupy as much<lb/>
                                        space as you can give me, but perhaps it would<lb/> be
                                        better to form some plan before we commence<lb/> Perhaps you
                                        would assign to me a certain number of<lb/> letters or a
                                        certain portion of your space and to an<lb/> opponent the
                                        same. If a place were thus formed and</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>published at the beginning, there might be more interest
                                        awaken-<lb/>ed for the Occident both among Jews and
                                        Christians. A regular<lb/> discussion on a proposed question
                                        would certainly be more<lb/> interesting than the irregular
                                        attacks of the past.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Dr. Shlesinger</persName> was anxious to
                                        know if I intended<lb/> to reply to his letter. I read to
                                        him nearly all the com-<lb/>munication which I proposed in
                                        my last letter to you, to pub-<lb/>lish, he appears to be
                                        much interested in the matter, and<lb/> if it comes
                                        prominently before the public, he will in<lb/> all
                                        probability make a reply.â€”He has visited me<lb/> very
                                        frequently during my confinement, and I feel very much
                                        attached to him.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">You will continue to send the Occident to
                                        myself<lb/> and my father during the coming year</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Please reply to this at your first convenience</p>
                              <p rend="indent(7)">Yours very truly</p>
                              <p rend="indent(7)">
                                        <persName role="author">M. R. Miller</persName>
                              </p>
